# Custom placement benchmarks

Hand-written LEF/DEF designs used to exercise specific placement conditions
that the ICCAD04 suite cannot isolate. Most benchmarks fit the FPGA CG
accelerator's default `MAX_N = 50` cell limit; `parallel_chains_75`
intentionally exceeds that to exercise larger `p_max_n` bitstreams (rebuild
the mmap driver via `run-placer fpga --p-max-n N`). All benchmarks stay
within the +/-4096 range of the Q13.14 fixed-point format used on the
board.

The HPS C++ placer reinitializes every cell to the die center on each run
([`init_cell_positions()`](../../sw-baseline-c/placer.cpp)), so the `PLACED`
coordinates inside each DEF are cosmetic -- only the die area, cell sizes,
and netlist connectivity drive the placement result.

Each benchmark is laid out as `<name>/{lef,def}/<name>.{lef,def}`. Run any
of them with:

```bash
uv run run-placer sw        ../benchmarks/custom/<name>      # CPU double-precision CG
uv run run-placer golden    ../benchmarks/custom/<name>      # CPU fixed-point golden CG
uv run run-placer verilated ../benchmarks/custom/<name>      # Verilator HW CG
uv run run-placer fpga      ../benchmarks/custom/<name>      # DE1-SoC HW CG
```

## At a glance

| Benchmark | Cells | Cell sizes (microns) | Die (DBU) | IOs | Nets | What it stresses |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| [simple_logic_10](simple_logic_10/) | 10 | INV 1.0x1.0, BUF/NAND2 2.0x1.0 | 2000x2000 | 6 | 13 | smallest end-to-end test, branching netlist |
| [mixed_macro_10](mixed_macro_10/) | 10 | INV/AND2/OR2 + WIDE 4.0x2.0 macro | 3000x2000 | 8 | 14 | one large macro mixed with std cells |
| [parallel_chains_50](parallel_chains_50/) | 50 | INV 0.1x0.1, BUF/NAND2 0.2x0.1 | 500x500 | 10 | 55 | five pipelined chains, cross-coupled at every stage |
| [parallel_chains_75](parallel_chains_75/) | 75 | INV 0.1x0.1, BUF/NAND2 0.2x0.1 | 500x500 | 10 | 84 | parallel_chains_50 extended to 15 stages (>MAX_N=50) |
| [mesh_grid_25](mesh_grid_25/) | 25 | GATE2 0.1x0.1 | 500x500 | 20 | 35 | 5x5 2D mesh -- each cell pulled by its top + left neighbor |
| [dense_pack_36](dense_pack_36/) | 36 | MED 0.4x0.4 | 500x500 | 2 | 37 | uniform medium cells, ~23% area utilization |
| [size_extremes_mix](size_extremes_mix/) | 34 | HUGE 1.5x1.5 + TINY 0.05x0.05 | 500x500 | 8 | 38 | 4 large macros each anchoring a cluster of tinies |
| [star_fanout_31](star_fanout_31/) | 31 | DRIVER 0.2x0.1 + 30 RECV 0.1x0.1 | 500x500 | 7 | 8 | single 31-pin fanout net (high net degree) |
| [two_clusters_bridge](two_clusters_bridge/) | 32 | CELL 0.1x0.1 | 500x500 | 4 | 34 | two 16-cell cliques joined by exactly one bridge net |

The first three are the original hand-written tests (formerly `tiny1`,
`tiny2`, `tiny3`); the rest are size/topology probes added later.

## Per-benchmark notes

### simple_logic_10

Ten gates -- a few INVs and a couple of BUF/NAND2 -- arranged on a
4x10^6 DBU^2 die so that the placer is essentially unconstrained by
density. Fanout is shallow (most nets are 2-3 pins), with a small amount of
re-convergence (`U6 -> U8/U9`). Useful as the smallest end-to-end smoke
test for any new backend.

### mixed_macro_10

Same scale as `simple_logic_10` but introduces a `WIDE` 4.0x2.0 macro
(4x bigger than INV in each dimension) alongside the std cells. Two `WIDE`
instances act as the chain endpoints, so the placer has to treat them as
strong "anchors" that the surrounding std cells migrate toward. Smallest
benchmark with a real macro/std-cell size disparity.

### parallel_chains_50

Fifty cells split into five parallel 10-stage pipelines. Each pipeline
takes one input pin on the left edge, runs a chain of INV/BUF/NAND2, and
drives one output pin on the right. Adjacent chains share a NAND2 input
pin per stage, creating mild cross-coupling. This is the primary "default"
benchmark referenced throughout the v2/v3/v4/v5 dev notes -- it's the
largest design that fits in the FPGA's 50-cell cap and exercises both
SPMV (50 rows) and AXPY/VecDot at full `p_lanes` width.

### parallel_chains_75

Same five-chain layout as `parallel_chains_50`, extended to 15 stages per
chain (75 cells, 84 nets). The chain-internal connectivity matches the
50-cell version: chain 0 has the BUF feeding the first NAND2's B locally;
chains 1-4 use the parallel-path entry pattern (BUF skips the first NAND2,
the first NAND2's B is fed exclusively by cross-coupling). Designed to
exceed the default `MAX_N = 50` so it only runs on bitstreams synthesized
with a larger `p_max_n` (and the matching `--p-max-n` driver rebuild).

### mesh_grid_25

A 5x5 grid of identical 0.1x0.1 GATE2 cells (A, B inputs, Y output).
Each cell at row `r`, col `c` takes its A from cell `(r-1, c)` (or top
input pin if `r == 0`) and its B from cell `(r, c-1)` (or left input
pin if `c == 0`). Y drives the cell below, the cell to the right, and
any matching right-edge or bottom-edge output pin. Stresses 2D placement
structure: no chain ordering, just a balanced lattice with 20 IO anchors
distributed around all four edges.

### dense_pack_36

Thirty-six 0.4x0.4 cells in a 36-stage pipelined chain on a 5x5-micron
die. Total cell area is ~5.76 microns^2 of a 25-micron^2 die -- ~23%
utilization. Cells are individually large enough that the placer cannot
collapse them all near the centroid; spreading happens naturally during
the legalization phase. The straight chain plus the high per-cell density
makes this the closest custom analogue to the ICCAD04 row-bound layouts.

### size_extremes_mix

Four 1.5x1.5 HUGE macros plus thirty 0.05x0.05 TINY std cells. Each HUGE
macro fans out from its 4-bit input bus to a cluster of seven tinies via
short Y0/Y1/Y2/Y3 chains; the cluster terminus drives one output pin.
Two extra tinies bridge cluster 0's leaf to cluster 1's via a short
`extra_a -> extra_b` chain. Exercises the placer's handling of extreme
size disparity (30x linear in each dimension) and clustered hub-and-spoke
attraction.

### star_fanout_31

One 0.2x0.1 DRIVER cell whose Y output drives a single 31-pin net
spanning all thirty 0.1x0.1 RECV cells. The receivers are split into six
groups of five, each group's Y outputs collected into one of six output
pins on the right edge. The high-degree fanout net is the dominant term
in the Q matrix, so the placer should park the driver near the centroid
of the receivers -- which themselves are pulled toward their respective
right-edge output pins. CG takes noticeably more iterations to converge
here than on the chain/mesh designs because of the dense fanout clique.

### two_clusters_bridge

Thirty-two 0.1x0.1 CELL instances split into two clusters of sixteen
(`A1..A16` and `B1..B16`). Within each cluster, a hub cell (`A1`/`B1`)
fans out to all fifteen siblings (the `hubA_fan` / `hubB_fan` nets),
and the siblings form a daisy-chained ring back through `A_N.Y` /
`B_N.Y`. Inputs `inA`/`inB` and outputs `outA`/`outB` are pinned on
opposite die edges. The single bridge connection is the `outA` net
itself -- it terminates at the left output pin **and** at `B1.B`,
weakly coupling the two clusters. The expected solution is two dense
blobs, with the bridge cells (`A_N` and `B1`) drawn toward each other.

## Adding a new benchmark

1. Create `benchmarks/custom/<name>/{lef,def}` and write `<name>.lef`
   (one MACRO per cell type) and `<name>.def` (with `DESIGN <name>;`,
   matching `DIEAREA`, COMPONENTS / PINS / NETS sections).
2. Verify the LEF/DEF parses with
   `uv run lefdef-parser benchmarks/custom/<name>` (writes
   `<name>.json` with the canonical schema).
3. Sanity-check on the SW placer with
   `uv run run-placer sw ../benchmarks/custom/<name>` from a `build/`
   directory; the run should print `=== Done ===` and write
   `<name>-initial.json` + `<name>-final.json`.
4. Visualize with `uv run visualizer build/<name>-final.json`.
5. Keep the bitstream's synthesized `p_max_n` (default 50) in mind if you
   plan to run on the FPGA or Verilator HW CG. Designs with more cells
   require either the SW solver or a bitstream + driver rebuilt at a
   larger `--p-max-n`.
